[2
Date: Wed, 27 Oct 1999 09:13:44 -0400
From: Joseph R Parrish Jr <JoeParrish@compuserve.com>

In New York City's City Council meeting 12 Oct 1999 regarding the mosquito
spraying [to stop the transmission of West Nile virus it was noted that
pesticide concentrations in the air we breathe are greatly increased when
the pesticides are sprayed in confined spaces. In the meeting,
toxicologist Robert Simon condemned spraying in subway tunnels where there
is limited air volume, and thus probable concentrations of pesticides to be
inhaled far above any proof of safety data for any given pesticide.
[The first ref. above indicates that one could be subjected to even higher
concentrations of pesticides for inhalation when an airplane is sprayed
with passengers inside it. There is a need for immediate review of all
pesticides being sprayed in such confined spaces to assure that there is
sufficient health data for the given pesticide to show it is indeed not
toxic to human health.
This is clearly not the case for the EPA's data on malathion. There is
considerable concern particularly about malathion's teratological impact
upon women in their second trimester of pregnancy, where malathion is
apparently known to produce defects in the fetal gastrointestinal tract.
The use of pesticides is becoming far too extensive for the current level
of submission of teratological and other toxicological data to demonstrate
the necessary safety for human health. Such data have not been made
available to the EPA in the case of malathion. Immediate steps need to be
taken to reign in the use of pesticides in closed spaces and over large
populations when the safety data are inadequate to assure human health.
Malathion in particular should be banned completely.
--
Joe Parrish, Ph.D.
NY/NJ Environmental Watch
300 East 56th Street
New York, NY 10022
and
St. John's Church
61 Broad Street
Elizabeth, NJ 07201
