[3
Date: Fri, 29 Oct 1999 16:17:48 +1000
From: Pat.Boland@aqis.gov.au

I write to clarify the position with regard to Australian policy and
practice on disinsection of aircraft.
The Australian Quarantine and Inspection Service (AQIS) requires
disinsection of the cabins and holds of incoming aircraft. Disinsection is
done by the airline and may take a number of forms, some of which would not
be apparent to the passenger. A fairly full description of the Australian
procedures is available on the internet at
http://www.aqis.gov.au/docs/border/aaircr.htm
In brief, the airline has the option of using either a quick knock-down
space spray or a residual surface spray before take-off on the last leg of
the journey to Australia. The practice is regularly monitored by AQIS staff
on arrival of the aircraft and is subject to an operational audit.
[Monitored how on arrival? By checking empty spray cans? - Mod.JW
Disinsection of aircraft has been practised in one form or another for a
long time. The 1933 edition of the International Sanitary Convention for
Aerial Navigation included the first published protocol for aircraft
disinsection. The World Health Organization has played an important role
in developing effective and standardised disinsection procedures. The
threats posed by insects which travel on aircraft are difficult to quantify
but the majority of reviews in this country over the last two decades have
supported the continuation of the practice. Target organisms include
mosquitoes, both endemic and exotic species, which are capable of
transmitting diseases, as well as agricultural pests, those which move
around during the flight being more susceptible to the process.
David Sencer [Ref: West Nile-like virus, aircraft spraying (02) above has
questioned the efficacy of the disinsection process (a space spray in his
case) which failed to kill samples of mosquitoes in his pocket or in the
overhead locker. If these mosquitoes were in closed boxes, their survival
is not surprising. If they were in exposed screened containers, they
should have been killed by a space spray but not necessarily by a residual
surface spray.
--
Pat Boland
Senior Veterinary Officer
Australian Quarantine and Inspection Service (AQIS)
Canberra, Australia
e-mail: pat.boland@aqis.gov.au
